<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-02-18T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-02-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="833" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d833">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6180.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-18T16:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 18, 1913—4 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>11. Your February 16, 11 a.m. The Department compliments you upon your
                            success in arranging an armistice and the prompt and efficient way in
                            which foreigners were removed from danger zones and arrangements were
                            made for the transportation of American women and children to the United
                            States.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—At this point a military interregnum
                                occurs, lasting a day and a half.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>